00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:13.690
So here we are with the
individual cubic lattices

00:02:13.690 --> 00:02:15.040
where we're going to focus.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:18.190
And we started looking at the
properties of cubic lattices.

00:02:18.190 --> 00:02:22.620
And I started working
through this table.

00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:26.140
And we got down to nearest
neighbors, and so on, and this

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:28.260
relationship between
the lattice

00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:29.770
constant and the radius.

00:02:29.770 --> 00:02:32.320
And I just wanted to show
this last point here

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:33.580
about packing density.

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:40.340
Because it comes up
considerations of properties

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:41.460
of elements.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:43.570
And so I wanted to go through
the packing density

00:02:43.570 --> 00:02:44.770
calculation.

00:02:44.770 --> 00:02:47.570
And so the way we handle the
packing density, remember

00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:49.890
we're looking at a
unit cell here.

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:52.820
This is the cube that's
the repeat unit.

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:55.870
And it has a lattice constant
of dimension a.

00:02:55.870 --> 00:02:59.000
And then depending on where we
put atoms, I want to show that

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.040
we've got three different
options here, simple cubic,

00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:04.350
body-centered cubic, and
face-centered cubic.

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:07.870
And the last line of that slide
shows that the densest

00:03:07.870 --> 00:03:09.555
packing of atoms-- this is hard

00:03:09.555 --> 00:03:11.490
spheres, the cannon balls--

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:13.450
the densest packing is
face-centered cubic.

00:03:13.450 --> 00:03:16.760
And I wanted to show the
derivation of that where if we

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:19.940
face-centered cubic where the
atoms are big enough to touch.

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:23.310
If we have 4 atoms at the corner
touching on the face

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:26.950
diagonal and then continuing
through the cell, we want to

00:03:26.950 --> 00:03:34.680
get packing density as the ratio
of the volume occupied

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:36.640
by the atoms-- and here
we're modeling the

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:38.240
atoms as hard spheres--

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.610
divided by the volume
of the cell itself.

00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:44.680
And so that's pretty
straightforward calculation.

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:47.290
We're modeling the atoms
as hard spheres.

00:03:47.290 --> 00:03:51.570
And we saw last day that if we
take the fraction of the atom,

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:55.970
1/8 times 1/8, and 6 times
1/2, we have 4 atom

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:57.510
equivalents per unit cell.

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:01.910
And each of these has a volume
of 4/3 pi r cubed.

00:04:01.910 --> 00:04:04.360
And then we divide
that by a cubed.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.460
And then we know the
relationship between a and r.

00:04:07.460 --> 00:04:09.540
This is 4r and that's
root 2 a.

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:13.260
So we can say root
2 a equals 4r.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:15.800
Either eliminate a
or eliminate r.

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:18.310
We eventually end up with this
dimensionless group, which is

00:04:18.310 --> 00:04:21.510
pi divided by 3 roots of 2.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:25.040
And that is 74%.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:26.405
And that's the densest
package.

00:04:26.405 --> 00:04:28.740
If you go through the same
calculation for body-centered

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:32.160
packing, you'll find
it's 68% packing.

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:35.120
And for simple cubic
it's 52% packing.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:39.130
That's the highest density that
you can have. So I urge

00:04:39.130 --> 00:04:40.140
you to spend some time.

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:42.900
If you work the homework, you'll
work your way through

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:44.110
that chart.

00:04:44.110 --> 00:04:47.130
So now I wanted to take a few
minutes and talk about

00:04:47.130 --> 00:04:48.660
crystallographic notation.

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:52.040
Because we need to know this in
order to describe various

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:53.060
features of a cell.

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:57.950
So I'm going to start with a
Cartesian coordinate system

00:04:57.950 --> 00:04:59.600
that obeys the right-hand
rule.

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:02.310
So we'll put down x, y and z.

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:07.010
And then we'll put up a unit
cell here with edge a.

00:05:07.010 --> 00:05:12.280
So we have a on the x,
y and z coordinate.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:16.010
And we know that a equals
b equals c.

00:05:16.010 --> 00:05:17.420
That's the unit vectors here.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:19.810
There's a little a here,
a little b here,

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:20.970
and a little c here.

00:05:20.970 --> 00:05:25.160
These are all equal to the
lattice constant value a.

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:27.240
And all of the angles
are 90 degrees.

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:29.430
This is what defines
the cubic system.

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:32.150
So I'm going to put several
positions here.

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:34.150
So here is the origin.

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:38.710
And the origin we designate
as 0, 0, 0.

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:41.170
I'm going to put a position
up here, a.

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.050
And you just use the same
notation as you'd use

00:05:44.050 --> 00:05:44.810
mathematics.

00:05:44.810 --> 00:05:48.150
Only crystallographers don't
put parentheses around it.

00:05:48.150 --> 00:05:49.990
So what I'm really teaching
is notation.

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:51.630
You already know the math.

00:05:51.630 --> 00:05:54.230
So a up here is what?

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:56.130
It's 0 units on the x-axis.

00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:59.150
It's 1 unit on the y-axis,
and 1 unit on a z-axis.

00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:01.820
So that would make it 0, 1, 1.

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:04.550
And I'm going to put
a b out here.

00:06:04.550 --> 00:06:07.700
B is out 1 unit on the x-axis.

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:10.350
It's 0 units on the y-axis.

00:06:10.350 --> 00:06:14.890
And it looks like it's up at
about 1/2 unit on the z-axis.

00:06:14.890 --> 00:06:18.390
So that makes 1, 0, and 1/2.

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:21.810
And so now what I want to do is
show you how we designate

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:24.275
directions and planes.

00:06:24.275 --> 00:06:26.690
You use a slightly different
notation from what

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:27.910
you used to in math.

00:06:27.910 --> 00:06:31.650
So this chart will be posted
at the website.

00:06:31.650 --> 00:06:34.480
Move the coordinate axes so the
line passes through the

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:38.400
origin, define a vector from the
origin to the point on the

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:40.580
line, and choose the smaller
set of integers.

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:42.440
So let's do a simple one here.

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:46.020
Let's do from origin to b.

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:47.720
So o to b.

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:49.500
That's this vector here.

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:50.620
So how would we do that one?

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:52.640
Well we're already
at the origin.

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:53.310
So that's trivial.

00:06:53.310 --> 00:06:56.410
o to b, so we're going from
here out to here.

00:06:56.410 --> 00:06:57.820
And then what does it say?

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:02.140
It says choose the smallest set
of integers, no commas,

00:07:02.140 --> 00:07:03.100
clear fractions.

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:06.980
So that's going to take
us out to 1 0 1/2.

00:07:06.980 --> 00:07:09.725
But the crystallographers
don't like fractions.

00:07:09.725 --> 00:07:11.610
So you're supposed to
clear the fractions.

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:14.140
You clear the fractions by
multiplying through.

00:07:14.140 --> 00:07:17.410
So make that 2 0 1.

00:07:17.410 --> 00:07:18.650
It's the same direction.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:20.980
See if I came out two units
here, I'd end up

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:21.970
being one unit here.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:24.850
So it's the same direction.

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:26.400
It really is the
same direction.

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:27.780
Don't put any commas.

00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:29.090
And put brackets around it.

00:07:29.090 --> 00:07:33.640
So that's the 2, 0, 1 direction,
which is o b.

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:34.800
And I want to do a
different one.

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:37.690
I'm going to go this
way, a to o.

00:07:37.690 --> 00:07:41.240
So let's look at
that one, a o.

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:42.620
And what happens on a o?

00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:44.720
Well now I'm going to
put the origin at a.

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:48.590
I'm going to go to
0 in the x-axis.

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:51.350
I'm going to go minus
1 in the z-axis, and

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:52.790
minus 1 in the y-axis.

00:07:52.790 --> 00:07:56.510
So that gives me 0
minus 1 minus 1.

00:07:56.510 --> 00:07:58.290
But see they don't use commas.

00:07:58.290 --> 00:07:59.940
And so this looks
kind of goofy.

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:01.440
Because you get these
minus signs in here.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:04.090
So what the crystallographers do
is they put the minus sign

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:05.340
on top of the number.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:09.000
So this becomes 0 1
with a macron it.

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:14.780
If you'd studied Latin, you'd
know this thing is a macron, a

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:16.800
line over a vowel.

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:19.490
So 0 1 bar 1 bar.

00:08:19.490 --> 00:08:21.760
And that's the direction a o.

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:25.430
So that's the macron acting
as the minus sign.

00:08:25.430 --> 00:08:28.790
So that's the a o direction

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:32.200
And then furthermore, we
can designate families.

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.780
This is just the
0 1 bar 1 bar.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:38.200
If you want to be a hipster
with crystallography,

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:39.380
you call this 0.

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:41.870
You say it's 0 1 bar 1 bar.

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:44.690
But if you're a nice chemistry
student, you'll say zero,

00:08:44.690 --> 00:08:46.510
minus 1 minus 1.

00:08:46.510 --> 00:08:49.710
No we don't do that in
3.091, 0 1 bar 1 bar.

00:08:49.710 --> 00:08:54.250
Now suppose I wanted to describe
all of the faces,

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:55.560
every face.

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:58.210
So what I could do, is I
could say I want the

00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:02.158
set of all face diagonals.

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:07.480
Well, that's a face diagonal.

00:09:07.480 --> 00:09:11.200
But what I can do is in a
compact notation, I could

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:17.180
write 0 1 1 and use the carat.

00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:20.300
This is called the carat.

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:24.560
So if I enclose in carats, this
means the set up all 0 1

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:26.410
1 type planes.

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:30.320
And so what that means is I can
unpack that, and write 0 1

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:37.790
1, 0 1 1 bar, 0 1 bar
1, et cetera.

00:09:37.790 --> 00:09:40.420
And what I'll end up doing
is describing the

00:09:40.420 --> 00:09:42.780
set up all face diagonals.

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:45.470
So if I want to talk to you
later when we're studying

00:09:45.470 --> 00:09:48.600
x-ray diffraction, I want to
talk about face diagonals, I

00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:49.530
don't use that word.

00:09:49.530 --> 00:09:50.950
We're quantitative
here at MIT.

00:09:50.950 --> 00:09:53.970
I say look at the
0 1 1 planes.

00:09:53.970 --> 00:09:55.780
So you go face diagonals.

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:57.850
That's the compact notation.

00:09:57.850 --> 00:10:05.130
If we want to look at all cell
edges, what's the cell edge?

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:07.090
Here's the cell edge.

00:10:07.090 --> 00:10:08.910
This is an edge here,
isn't it?

00:10:08.910 --> 00:10:10.060
It's right on the edge
of the cell.

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:12.880
So it's 0 on the
y, 0 in the z.

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:14.290
It's 1 in the x.

00:10:14.290 --> 00:10:19.620
So the set of all cell
edges would be 0 0 1.

00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:22.210
And you could write 1
0 0, that's OK too.

00:10:22.210 --> 00:10:23.540
Or you could write 0 1 0.

00:10:23.540 --> 00:10:24.460
That's OK.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:27.050
But if you want to be a hipster
in crystallography,

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:28.710
put the zeroes out in front.

00:10:28.710 --> 00:10:33.710
So the set of 0 0 1 directions
is all the cube edges.

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:37.400
And then lastly, if we wanted to
get all the diagonals that

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:42.540
starts from here and goes up,
we'll have all cell diagonals,

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:45.430
all, if you want to call it,
body diagonals, not face

00:10:45.430 --> 00:10:48.890
diagonals, body diagonals.

00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:51.250
Body diagonals is 1 1 1.

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:53.130
And the mathematics
imitates reality.

00:10:53.130 --> 00:10:55.240
How many combinations
are there here?

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:58.380
I've got 0 1, and I've
got minus 1.

00:10:58.380 --> 00:11:03.510
So I have 0 0 1, 0 0 1 bar,
0 1 0, 0 1 bar 0,

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:04.695
1 0 0, 1 bar 0.

00:11:04.695 --> 00:11:07.020
There's 6 And how many
edges are there?

00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:08.070
6.

00:11:08.070 --> 00:11:10.990
Mathematics imitating reality,
what a concept.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:11.930
That's great.

00:11:11.930 --> 00:11:12.870
OK.

00:11:12.870 --> 00:11:13.510
So that's good.

00:11:13.510 --> 00:11:15.630
Now we want to look at planes.

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:17.010
Let's look at planes.

00:11:17.010 --> 00:11:18.550
Now planes are a little
bit different.

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:21.250
This is basically what you know
from math with a little

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:24.600
bit of notation It's basically
the same thing.

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:25.700
Planes are quite different.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:27.540
So let's go to the planes.

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:29.170
So you know the equation
of a plane.

00:11:29.170 --> 00:11:34.870
It's x over a plus y over b
plus z over c equals 1.

00:11:34.870 --> 00:11:39.530
And a b and c are the intercepts
at the x, y z axes.

00:11:39.530 --> 00:11:44.950
Well, in order to make this
notation compatible to what we

00:11:44.950 --> 00:11:48.430
have here for lines, a British
meteorologist by the name of

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:53.550
William Hallowes Miller in 1839
said let's define h, k,

00:11:53.550 --> 00:11:56.880
and l as the reciprocals
of these intercepts.

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:01.960
And now we'll write the equation
of a plane as hx plus

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:04.580
ky plus lz equals 1.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:09.440
And we'll use those values of h,
k, and l as the indicators

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:09.940
of a plane.

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:12.640
So here's an example.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:17.110
So again, I've got the
right-handed rule coordinates.

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:18.550
And here's the plane.

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:21.360
And you can see that it
cuts the x-axis and a.

00:12:21.360 --> 00:12:23.310
It cuts the y-axis at b.

00:12:23.310 --> 00:12:24.710
And it's parallel
to the z-axis.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:30.810
So if we were just to use the
old mathematics notation, and

00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:34.350
put the a, b and c, you'd
have 1/2 here.

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:35.220
You'd have 1 here.

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:36.420
And you'd have infinity here.

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:38.080
And that looks goofy.

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:41.150
So instead what we want to do
is use the Miller indices,

00:12:41.150 --> 00:12:43.170
which are the reciprocals.

00:12:43.170 --> 00:12:46.150
So now the reciprocal
of 1/2 is 2.

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:48.330
The reciprocal of 1
trivially is 1.

00:12:48.330 --> 00:12:51.100
And the reciprocal
of infinity is 0.

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:53.060
And so now you have something
that makes sense.

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:55.430
And you put no commas
in between.

00:12:55.430 --> 00:12:57.800
And you put the whole thing
in parentheses.

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:01.110
So that's the 2 1 0 plane.

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:03.430
And there's a really
cool property here.

00:13:03.430 --> 00:13:07.810
And that is, using this same
formulation I just showed you

00:13:07.810 --> 00:13:11.560
for directions, the 2 1 0
directions-- you see 2 1 0

00:13:11.560 --> 00:13:13.880
with square brackets,
that's a direction.

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:16.140
2 1 0 with parentheses
is a plane.

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:19.390
The 2 1 0 direction
is perpendicular

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:21.320
to the 2 1 0 plane.

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:23.430
And that's one of the advantages
of using Miller

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.030
indices notation with
the classical

00:13:26.030 --> 00:13:28.710
notation for direction.

00:13:28.710 --> 00:13:29.460
Here's another one.

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:31.120
This is 0 1 0.

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:33.150
This is the x, y, and the z.

00:13:33.150 --> 00:13:35.760
So this cuts at 1, 0 1 0.

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:38.230
This is 0 2 0.

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:41.580
An 0 1 0 directions are
perpendicular to 0 1 0 plane.

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:45.100
0 2 0 directions are
perpendicular to 0 2 0 plane.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:47.520
Oh here's 1 1 1.

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:48.020
That's cool.

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.690
See it cuts it at 1 1 and 1.

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:55.730
And 1 1 1 direction cuts
through the 1 1 1 plane

00:13:55.730 --> 00:13:57.830
perpendicular.

00:13:57.830 --> 00:13:58.850
This is an interesting one.

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:00.290
See the origin.

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:01.940
The plane cuts through
the origin.

00:14:01.940 --> 00:14:03.740
Now what do you do?

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:04.780
What do you do?

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:08.000
You move the origin.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.900
Because we don't know where the
origin of the universe is.

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:10.840
It's just a unit cell.

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:11.360
It doesn't matter.

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:12.645
So we move the origin up here.

00:14:12.645 --> 00:14:13.760
And now what do we have?

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.420
We have 1 1 and minus 1.

00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:19.250
And just as before, we put
1 with a macron over it.

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:21.490
That's 1 1 1 bar plane.

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:23.860
And there is the 1 1
1 bar direction.

00:14:23.860 --> 00:14:24.700
It doesn't matter.

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:27.920
It'll always give you
perpendicular.

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:29.810
It's really cool.

00:14:29.810 --> 00:14:30.420
All right.

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:33.340
And we can also specify
a set of planes.

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:35.360
So instead of using
parentheses,

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:36.700
we use brace brackets.

00:14:36.700 --> 00:14:40.080
And if we use brae brackets,
we get families of planes.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:45.000
So for example, we could say if
we wanted a particular face

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:54.170
so that the face in the xy
plane, facing the xy plane

00:14:54.170 --> 00:14:55.720
would be 0 0 1.

00:14:55.720 --> 00:14:57.400
Right, because it cuts the z.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:14:58.610
So this is 0 0 1.

00:14:58.610 --> 00:15:02.360
But what if I wanted to say in
a compact way, all faces of

00:15:02.360 --> 00:15:04.710
the unit cell, all
of the faces.

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:06.450
So this is the particular
plane.

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:11.665
If I wanted to say all faces
I would write 0 0 1.

00:15:11.665 --> 00:15:15.005
But I can't use any of
these containers.

00:15:15.005 --> 00:15:16.560
So I'll use brace brackets.

00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:21.140
So 0 0 1 in brace brackets means
the whole setup, 0 0 1,

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:30.950
0 0 1 bar, 0 1 0, 0 1 bar
0, 1 0 0, and 1 bar 0 0.

00:15:30.950 --> 00:15:32.040
So there's only 6.

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:33.270
And there's 6 faces.

00:15:33.270 --> 00:15:36.200
Again mathematics imitating
reality.

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:36.960
What a concept.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:38.140
Make the math work for you.

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:39.600
You don't work for the math.

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:43.740
All right and just to make the
point about the h k l plane,

00:15:43.740 --> 00:15:48.610
is perpendicular to the
h k l direction.

00:15:48.610 --> 00:15:49.730
So that's good.

00:15:49.730 --> 00:15:51.960
And the last thing I want to
show you that comes out of the

00:15:51.960 --> 00:15:58.200
use of the Miller indices for
planes, is that another

00:15:58.200 --> 00:16:00.530
property that we'd
like to know is

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:02.150
the interplanar spacing.

00:16:02.150 --> 00:16:05.360
What's the spacing between
like planes.

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:15.810
So interplanar spacing, that is
to say the distance between

00:16:15.810 --> 00:16:27.426
like planes, adjacent planes
identical index.

00:16:33.470 --> 00:16:40.620
I'm going to write it to be
specific to say Miller index,

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:43.710
h k l in parentheses.

00:16:43.710 --> 00:16:45.760
And the property that comes out
of this-- and you don't

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:46.500
have to derive it.

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:49.530
Somebody worked this out for
you about a 150 years ago--

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:53.420
is that the distance between
adjacent planes with the index

00:16:53.420 --> 00:16:58.040
h k l is given by the ratio
of a, which is the lattice

00:16:58.040 --> 00:17:05.670
constant, this is the cubed
edge, divided by the sum of

00:17:05.670 --> 00:17:13.710
the squares of h, k, and l taken
to the power of 1/2, So

00:17:13.710 --> 00:17:16.520
the square root of h squared
plus k squared plus l squared

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:22.430
divided into the lattice
constant, gives you the value

00:17:22.430 --> 00:17:25.010
of the spacing in between.

00:17:25.010 --> 00:17:28.280
And this is the a just
to be clear about it.

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:32.686
So for example, I think I've
got some cartoons up

00:17:32.686 --> 00:17:33.900
here that show this.

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:35.080
So here's 0 1 0.

00:17:35.080 --> 00:17:35.720
It's trivial.

00:17:35.720 --> 00:17:37.860
What's the distance here?

00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:40.780
The d 0 1 0 is just day.

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:41.370
How about here?

00:17:41.370 --> 00:17:44.490
This is 0 squared, 2 squared.

00:17:44.490 --> 00:17:46.290
0 squared, this is d over 2.

00:17:46.290 --> 00:17:48.320
So this is a 0 2 0 plane.

00:17:48.320 --> 00:17:53.270
But if the distance between 0
2 0 planes is 1/2 a, well,

00:17:53.270 --> 00:17:54.970
then that's an 0 2 0 plane.

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:56.980
Then this is an 0 2 0 plane.

00:17:56.980 --> 00:18:00.960
So point of fact, every 0 1
0 plane is an 0 2 0 plane.

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:03.740
But every 0 2 0 plane isn't
an 0 1 0 plane.

00:18:03.740 --> 00:18:07.660
You can see that some planes
have multiple names.

00:18:07.660 --> 00:18:08.090
Here's another one.

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:11.650
Look, this is the distance
between adjacent 1 1 1 planes.

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:12.910
It's a over root 3.

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:16.620
So as the index goes up, as h
k l goes up, the distance

00:18:16.620 --> 00:18:18.590
between successive
planes goes down.

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:22.150
And the angle between
the planes goes up.

00:18:22.150 --> 00:18:24.240
The easiest one is orthogonal.

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:26.520
OK, that's good.

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:27.740
That's good.

00:18:27.740 --> 00:18:28.200
All right.

